WEBVTT

﻿1
00:00:04.129 --> 00:00:07.883
{\an8}[Luann] <i>There are two types of people
in this modern world of ours.</i>

2
00:00:08.509 --> 00:00:12.053
<i>The admirable hardworking
movers and shakers.</i>

3
00:00:12.054 --> 00:00:14.138
<i>and the poor.</i>

4
00:00:14.139 --> 00:00:15.431
<i>How I pity them.</i>

5
00:00:15.432 --> 00:00:18.268
<i>They don't have that killer instinct.</i>

6
00:00:19.102 --> 00:00:22.605
<i>The unmoneyed lack initiative. discipline.</i>

7
00:00:22.606 --> 00:00:24.899
<i>They just aren't shrewd.</i>

8
00:00:24.900 --> 00:00:29.695
The poor are content to file our
toenails and bleach our mustaches

9
00:00:29.696 --> 00:00:32.574
because they are too lazy
to reach for a better life.

10
00:00:34.326 --> 00:00:38.162
Ambition is the sole province of the rich.

11
00:00:38.163 --> 00:00:42.917
{\an8}Oh. hogwash. Take my son Seymour. the bum.

12
00:00:42.918 --> 00:00:45.461
{\an8}Majored in nepotism at Ditherton College.

13
00:00:45.462 --> 00:00:48.923
{\an8}All set to take over
the family prune canning business.

14
00:00:48.924 --> 00:00:50.132
{\an8}And where is he now?

15
00:00:50.133 --> 00:00:54.011
{\an8}Living off his trust on
the coast of Italy like some pope.

16
00:00:54.012 --> 00:00:57.098
{\an8}Ugh. Italians are so European.

17
00:00:57.099 --> 00:01:01.727
[sighs] I'd give a suitcase
full of simoleons to anyone

18
00:01:01.728 --> 00:01:04.731
who could bring that
pampered popinjay back home.

19
00:01:07.734 --> 00:01:10.736
{\an8}[cashier] Can I box that up for you.
Miss Van Houten?

20
00:01:10.737 --> 00:01:14.533
{\an8}It's "Mrs." And no. I'll wear it out.

21
00:01:15.200 --> 00:01:17.661
{\an8}Darling.
bring me one of these in polar bear.

22
00:01:18.453 --> 00:01:22.623
{\an8}[gasps]
Mrs. Skinner. as I live and breathe.

23
00:01:22.624 --> 00:01:24.458
{\an8}I'm sorry. Do I know you?

24
00:01:24.459 --> 00:01:26.085
{\an8}Marjorie Bouvier.

25
00:01:26.086 --> 00:01:28.421
{\an8}I'm an old friend of Seymour's.

26
00:01:28.422 --> 00:01:30.339
{\an8}We met at your charity ball for...

27
00:01:30.340 --> 00:01:32.133
{\an8}Oh. what was it?

28
00:01:32.134 --> 00:01:34.719
{\an8}The Policemen's Malevolent Association.

29
00:01:34.720 --> 00:01:38.598
{\an8}Yes. police violence is
such an important cause.

30
00:01:38.599 --> 00:01:40.516
{\an8}How is dear Seymour?

31
00:01:40.517 --> 00:01:43.394
{\an8}Ironing out
the wrinkles at the prune cannery?

32
00:01:43.395 --> 00:01:45.229
[sighs]

33
00:01:45.230 --> 00:01:49.066
I raised my little boy to
be a henpecked business wuss.

34
00:01:49.067 --> 00:01:50.652
but look at him now.

35
00:01:51.320 --> 00:01:52.737
[Marge] No socks?

36
00:01:52.738 --> 00:01:54.739
{\an8}Seymour has changed.

37
00:01:54.740 --> 00:01:58.576
{\an8}He says he's trying to be an
artist if you can believe it.

38
00:01:58.577 --> 00:02:02.497
{\an8}I was just summering in Italy.
If I'd known. I would have looked him up.

39
00:02:03.915 --> 00:02:06.792
{\an8}Marjorie.
this is probably too much to ask.

40
00:02:06.793 --> 00:02:08.794
{\an8}but what if I sent you

41
00:02:08.795 --> 00:02:13.090
{\an8}to Italy to find my wayward son
and convince him to come home?

42
00:02:13.091 --> 00:02:14.842
{\an8}All expenses paid of course.

43
00:02:14.843 --> 00:02:16.761
{\an8}Oh. my.

44
00:02:16.762 --> 00:02:18.763
{\an8}What an unexpected offer.

45
00:02:18.764 --> 00:02:21.850
{\an8}I'm desperate. dearie. What do you say?

46
00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:29.074
Do you want subtitles for any video?
-=[ ai.OpenSubtitles.com ]=-

47
00:02:31.109 --> 00:02:33.028
[♪ guitar playing]

48
00:02:40.869 --> 00:02:42.703
Seymour Skinner?

49
00:02:42.704 --> 00:02:45.539
What are you
doing on a beach in Bella Truffa?

50
00:02:45.540 --> 00:02:50.044
Hmm? I'd ask you the same if I had
the slightest clue who you are.

51
00:02:50.045 --> 00:02:51.462
Marge Bouvier.

52
00:02:51.463 --> 00:02:54.715
We met at Ditherton.
We were in the same econ class.

53
00:02:54.716 --> 00:02:56.217
I never took econ.

54
00:02:56.218 --> 00:02:59.720
Maybe I'm thinking of
statistics with Professor...

55
00:02:59.721 --> 00:03:00.971
Needlemeyer.

56
00:03:00.972 --> 00:03:03.474
Yes. I was a few rows behind you.

57
00:03:03.475 --> 00:03:05.309
I didn't take him. I had Gopnik.

58
00:03:05.310 --> 00:03:07.645
We had Gopnik. of course.

59
00:03:07.646 --> 00:03:08.979
As a private tutor.

60
00:03:08.980 --> 00:03:12.233
Um. me too. I had him right after you.

61
00:03:12.234 --> 00:03:13.944
Oh. of course.

62
00:03:14.778 --> 00:03:17.572
But Ditherton's a men's college.

63
00:03:18.907 --> 00:03:24.036
Yes. Which is why I dressed up
as a man in order to attend.

64
00:03:24.037 --> 00:03:26.455
To prove a point to the sexist dean.

65
00:03:26.456 --> 00:03:29.041
Ah. that explains it.
Nice to meet you again.

66
00:03:29.042 --> 00:03:30.459
Pull up some sand.

67
00:03:30.460 --> 00:03:33.129
Looks like I've made
another American friend.

68
00:03:33.130 --> 00:03:34.296
Another?

69
00:03:34.297 --> 00:03:38.217
Seymour. did you see me do a handstand?
Did you see? D... Who's this?

70
00:03:38.218 --> 00:03:40.553
Marge Bouvier. meet Homer Simpsley.

71
00:03:40.554 --> 00:03:43.139
Another well-to-do
friend I made in Napoli.

72
00:03:43.140 --> 00:03:47.852
He's become my travel companion. food
taster and. uh. temporary house guest.

73
00:03:47.853 --> 00:03:49.103
Permanent roommate.

74
00:03:49.104 --> 00:03:52.398
Come up to the house and have
some wine with us. You simply must.

75
00:03:52.399 --> 00:03:53.899
Uh. no. she mustn't.

76
00:03:53.900 --> 00:03:55.652
I'd love to.

77
00:03:56.236 --> 00:03:57.654
[♪ bossa nova playing]

78
00:03:59.156 --> 00:04:02.658
Great Gatsby! You live like this?

79
00:04:02.659 --> 00:04:04.869
But you don't even have a job.

80
00:04:04.870 --> 00:04:06.996
I mean. uh. nice place.

81
00:04:06.997 --> 00:04:08.205
Eh. it'll do.

82
00:04:08.206 --> 00:04:11.001
Now. let me take you to my studio.

83
00:04:11.585 --> 00:04:14.420
You're. uh. quite the prodigious painter.

84
00:04:14.421 --> 00:04:17.006
Yes. and Homer's quite the muse.

85
00:04:17.007 --> 00:04:18.757
The prominent curves.

86
00:04:18.758 --> 00:04:20.676
{\an8}The shadowy folds.

87
00:04:20.677 --> 00:04:22.929
And he can hold
absolutely still for hours.

88
00:04:23.472 --> 00:04:25.264
Oh. my.

89
00:04:25.265 --> 00:04:27.641
How bold of you to paint him in the nude.

90
00:04:27.642 --> 00:04:29.894
Actually. um. he insisted.

91
00:04:29.895 --> 00:04:31.188
[Homer] Painting time!

92
00:04:32.189 --> 00:04:34.357
Ugh. She's still here?

93
00:04:35.192 --> 00:04:36.777
[Marge] <i>Dear Mrs. Skinner.</i>

94
00:04:37.319 --> 00:04:40.154
<i>Good news. I found Seymour.</i>

95
00:04:40.155 --> 00:04:43.784
<i>Now. the hard work of
convincing him to come home can begin.</i>

96
00:04:44.367 --> 00:04:48.622
<i>I start most days on his beloved boat.
which he named in your honor.</i>

97
00:04:50.540 --> 00:04:53.126
<i>Then grab a light lunch at a cafe.</i>

98
00:04:55.128 --> 00:05:00.967
<i>Some days Seymour takes us on a day
trip to see a Caravaggio in all its glory.</i>

99
00:05:02.719 --> 00:05:07.682
<i>Your son's even taken on a young pupil.
Hoping to pass on his talent.</i>

100
00:05:08.725 --> 00:05:12.436
<i>Although Seymour lives quite
the dolce vita here.</i>

101
00:05:12.437 --> 00:05:15.899
<i>I'm sure I can get him back
to America in no time.</i>

102
00:05:16.775 --> 00:05:19.820
- A toast to never going back to America.
- [waves crashing]

103
00:05:20.946 --> 00:05:22.197
Time for a refill.

104
00:05:23.073 --> 00:05:25.825
Seymour said you came from money.

105
00:05:25.826 --> 00:05:28.911
Remind me what does your family do again?

106
00:05:28.912 --> 00:05:34.875
Uh. my wealthy family owns
a lucrative skull factory.

107
00:05:34.876 --> 00:05:37.795
Can't get ahead without a Simpsley skull.

108
00:05:37.796 --> 00:05:39.255
Hey. that's a pretty good lie.

109
00:05:39.256 --> 00:05:40.464
No. it wasn't.

110
00:05:40.465 --> 00:05:41.841
You're not rich.

111
00:05:41.842 --> 00:05:44.009
You're just a low-class mooch.

112
00:05:44.010 --> 00:05:46.220
[scoffs]
At least there's honor in mooching.

113
00:05:46.221 --> 00:05:48.389
You're nothing but a two-tit con man.

114
00:05:48.390 --> 00:05:51.892
[in Italian] Mr. Homer.
your fat is jiggling!

115
00:05:51.893 --> 00:05:55.062
[in English] As soon as Skinner
sees you for what you are.

116
00:05:55.063 --> 00:05:58.816
he's gonna toss you out like
yesterday's meatballs.

117
00:05:58.817 --> 00:06:00.818
but I'm not going anywhere.

118
00:06:00.819 --> 00:06:02.487
I'm his muse.

119
00:06:03.238 --> 00:06:04.364
Hmm.

120
00:06:09.828 --> 00:06:11.246
[♪ dramatic music plays]

121
00:06:11.830 --> 00:06:14.331
[gasps] Holy cannoli.

122
00:06:14.332 --> 00:06:16.083
Marge. you're an absolute vision.

123
00:06:16.084 --> 00:06:19.420
The light. the hair.
the discernible waistline.

124
00:06:19.421 --> 00:06:21.715
I must commit you to canvas.

125
00:06:22.340 --> 00:06:23.507
[grunts]

126
00:06:23.508 --> 00:06:26.010
Hey. I was musing there.

127
00:06:26.011 --> 00:06:28.512
Um. why don't you go eat. Homer?

128
00:06:28.513 --> 00:06:30.931
There's still some of
yesterday's meatballs.

129
00:06:30.932 --> 00:06:33.184
- [♪ dramatic music continues]
- [Marge] Mm-mmm.

130
00:06:37.063 --> 00:06:38.398
[grunting]

131
00:06:40.901 --> 00:06:42.819
[♪ Italian music playing]

132
00:06:49.117 --> 00:06:51.577
The mushrooms were super. Mario.

133
00:06:51.578 --> 00:06:55.497
[in Italian] My name is Wario. idiot! Wah!

134
00:06:55.498 --> 00:06:58.250
[in English] Seymour. darling.
now that we're living together.

135
00:06:58.251 --> 00:07:00.794
I think it's time Homer moved out.

136
00:07:00.795 --> 00:07:05.924
Mmm. He has been acting a bit
queer to use the parlance of our time.

137
00:07:05.925 --> 00:07:10.387
Plus. all those broken Vespas are
really a drain on your trust fund.

138
00:07:10.388 --> 00:07:12.765
- [bike rattles]
- [metal clanks]

139
00:07:12.766 --> 00:07:14.142
It happened again.

140
00:07:15.268 --> 00:07:17.019
Here's your laundry. Skinner.

141
00:07:17.020 --> 00:07:20.022
What's for lunch?
Oh. and don't say Italian.

142
00:07:20.023 --> 00:07:21.482
We ate.

143
00:07:21.483 --> 00:07:23.317
Go put Seymour's clothes away.

144
00:07:23.318 --> 00:07:26.612
We're gonna go lie on
the beach that stinks of fish.

145
00:07:26.613 --> 00:07:28.781
[grunts] Stupid Marge.

146
00:07:28.782 --> 00:07:32.409
Before she showed up.
things around here were a lot more gay

147
00:07:32.410 --> 00:07:34.286
to use the parlance of our time.

148
00:07:34.287 --> 00:07:37.040
Ooh. when did he get this?

149
00:07:38.458 --> 00:07:40.876
[imitating Skinner]
"Uh. do you like it. Homer?

150
00:07:40.877 --> 00:07:42.961
Marge finds it garish."

151
00:07:42.962 --> 00:07:45.381
[normal. scoffs] Her face is garish.

152
00:07:45.382 --> 00:07:48.051
[imitating Skinner. chuckles]
"You're incorrigible.

153
00:07:48.718 --> 00:07:52.888
Hmm. You know. I've been
thinking of ending things with her."

154
00:07:52.889 --> 00:07:55.016
[normal] Really? Why?

155
00:07:55.558 --> 00:07:58.018
[imitating Skinner]
"Well. I have my eye on someone else.

156
00:07:58.019 --> 00:08:00.355
Someone more full figured."

157
00:08:01.147 --> 00:08:04.109
[normal] What? [imitating Skinner.
shushes] "Just go with it."

158
00:08:04.901 --> 00:08:06.319
[moaning]

159
00:08:08.613 --> 00:08:13.951
[moaning. grunting] "Oh. yes. Homer."
Oh. Skinner.

160
00:08:13.952 --> 00:08:16.412
What the hell's going on here?

161
00:08:16.413 --> 00:08:18.539
[screams]
Seymour. it's not what you think!

162
00:08:18.540 --> 00:08:20.165
I mean nothing to me!

163
00:08:20.166 --> 00:08:23.502
- Take my clothes off this instant.
- Oh!

164
00:08:23.503 --> 00:08:25.921
Then get out of my villa.

165
00:08:25.922 --> 00:08:27.340
Aw!

166
00:08:27.966 --> 00:08:30.259
But-But we're best friends.

167
00:08:30.260 --> 00:08:34.471
I only tolerated your zaftig
buffoonery because you were easy to paint.

168
00:08:34.472 --> 00:08:38.727
You're just one circle on top of another.
Any idiot could draw you.

169
00:08:40.145 --> 00:08:41.228
[grunts]

170
00:08:41.229 --> 00:08:42.813
Marge was right.

171
00:08:42.814 --> 00:08:46.984
You're dumb as an ox.
unbelievably fat and charmlessly clingy.

172
00:08:46.985 --> 00:08:51.114
You're the most
repulsive person I've ever met.

173
00:08:54.284 --> 00:08:56.869
Guess we can add clumsy to the list too.

174
00:08:56.870 --> 00:09:00.581
Whoa. [yelling]

175
00:09:00.582 --> 00:09:01.916
[groaning]

176
00:09:04.711 --> 00:09:06.504
[clock chimes. cuckoos]

177
00:09:07.839 --> 00:09:09.340
[gasps]

178
00:09:13.344 --> 00:09:15.846
No. no. no. no. no. Seymour. please.

179
00:09:15.847 --> 00:09:17.264
Dear God.

180
00:09:17.265 --> 00:09:20.309
[gasps] I didn't do this.
He slapsticked himself to death.

181
00:09:20.310 --> 00:09:24.063
[Homer sobs]

182
00:09:24.064 --> 00:09:29.151
[sighs] Looks like our meal ticket just
got a big hole punched into it.

183
00:09:29.152 --> 00:09:33.155
Is that all you can think about.
you greedy shrew? You never loved him!

184
00:09:33.156 --> 00:09:36.075
[sobs] I call dibs on his room.

185
00:09:36.076 --> 00:09:38.827
Don't you get it? We're out on our ass.

186
00:09:38.828 --> 00:09:43.500
[groans] I guess it's back to filing down
corns and forging checks for me.

187
00:09:44.125 --> 00:09:50.756
Unless I was to fake Seymour's
signature on his monthly trust checks.

188
00:09:50.757 --> 00:09:52.883
But you can't pass for Skinner.

189
00:09:52.884 --> 00:09:55.219
You're a... [gags] ...woman.

190
00:09:55.220 --> 00:09:57.930
I can't. but you can.

191
00:09:57.931 --> 00:10:00.474
[gasps] I'd be the Seymour?

192
00:10:00.475 --> 00:10:03.393
Then we wouldn't be
mooching off the rich anymore.

193
00:10:03.394 --> 00:10:06.396
- We'd be one of them.
- One of them.

194
00:10:06.397 --> 00:10:10.400
[groans] What's that now?

195
00:10:10.401 --> 00:10:11.735
Hmm.

196
00:10:11.736 --> 00:10:15.656
It'd be a shame to waste a clever plan.

197
00:10:15.657 --> 00:10:17.116
Oh. yeah.

198
00:10:17.117 --> 00:10:20.495
We'd kick ourselves
later if we didn't at least try.

199
00:10:23.289 --> 00:10:27.252
[muffled straining]

200
00:10:29.003 --> 00:10:30.170
[both grunt]

201
00:10:30.171 --> 00:10:33.924
This little scheme of ours only works if
we stick together.

202
00:10:33.925 --> 00:10:35.551
For better or for worse.

203
00:10:35.552 --> 00:10:36.845
What are you proposing?

204
00:10:39.931 --> 00:10:42.474
[gasps] What? Are you proposing?

205
00:10:42.475 --> 00:10:45.186
[laughs]

206
00:10:45.854 --> 00:10:46.896
[both grunt]

207
00:10:48.231 --> 00:10:51.441
[Skinner] <i>Dearest Mother.
forgive my delayed correspondence.</i>

208
00:10:51.442 --> 00:10:53.862
<i>but the most wonderful
thing has happened to me.</i>

209
00:10:54.445 --> 00:10:58.283
<i>I've fallen deeply.
swiftly and profoundly in love.</i>

210
00:10:58.950 --> 00:11:00.742
<i>And I've gotten married.</i>

211
00:11:00.743 --> 00:11:04.372
<i>The priest said he never saw
a couple so smitten with each other.</i>

212
00:11:04.998 --> 00:11:08.292
<i>We're packing only the essentials
as we leave on our honeymoon.</i>

213
00:11:08.293 --> 00:11:10.127
<i>I'll let you know where we land.</i>

214
00:11:10.128 --> 00:11:11.545
<i>Love. Seymour.</i>

215
00:11:11.546 --> 00:11:14.299
<i>P.S.. I am alive.</i>

216
00:11:15.300 --> 00:11:17.384
[train whistle blows]

217
00:11:17.385 --> 00:11:21.805
Our first stop in Rome will be the bank.
signor Skinner.

218
00:11:21.806 --> 00:11:23.432
But I don't look anything like him.

219
00:11:23.433 --> 00:11:25.142
You do now.

220
00:11:25.143 --> 00:11:27.729
Ooh. baby. [kisses]

221
00:11:31.983 --> 00:11:35.402
[imitating Skinner] Uh. I'd like
to take some money out of my trust.

222
00:11:35.403 --> 00:11:38.405
My name is Seymour Skinner.

223
00:11:38.406 --> 00:11:40.700
Account number and passport please.

224
00:11:42.660 --> 00:11:45.538
Hmm. Eh. Close enough.

225
00:11:46.831 --> 00:11:48.541
Sign here. Mr. Skinner.

226
00:11:52.754 --> 00:11:54.796
I love your jacket.

227
00:11:54.797 --> 00:11:57.049
Is the back the same color as the front?

228
00:11:57.050 --> 00:11:59.802
<i>Sì. sì.</i> I will show you. Hmm.

229
00:12:05.058 --> 00:12:06.892
Hmm. I get your money.

230
00:12:06.893 --> 00:12:08.394
[♪ Italian music playing]

231
00:12:28.456 --> 00:12:31.583
More bubbly for my co-conspirator?

232
00:12:31.584 --> 00:12:35.128
You know. that suit makes
you look like a movie star.

233
00:12:35.129 --> 00:12:40.217
Like Fatty Arbuckle or that
Italian actor Lardo Disgusto.

234
00:12:40.218 --> 00:12:44.304
Oh. well.
this toupee is kinda itchy though.

235
00:12:44.305 --> 00:12:47.516
No. no. no. Leave it on. Seymour.

236
00:12:47.517 --> 00:12:50.394
[laughs] Yeah.

237
00:12:50.395 --> 00:12:51.603
Call me that again.

238
00:12:51.604 --> 00:12:55.691
Didn't it feel good to get
away with something. Seymour?

239
00:12:55.692 --> 00:12:59.403
[kisses] And we did it together. Seymour.

240
00:12:59.404 --> 00:13:01.196
Oh. baby.

241
00:13:01.197 --> 00:13:04.325
[kissing] Oh. Oh. Seymour.

242
00:13:05.451 --> 00:13:06.953
Just like that. Seymour.

243
00:13:07.620 --> 00:13:11.373
Wait. wait. Can I call you Seymour too?

244
00:13:11.374 --> 00:13:14.334
- Um. sure.
- Okay.

245
00:13:14.335 --> 00:13:16.837
- Oh. Seymour. Devour me. Seymour
- Oh. Seymour. Yes.

246
00:13:16.838 --> 00:13:18.839
Oh. you boring. boring man.

247
00:13:18.840 --> 00:13:21.967
- Oh. Seymour. your kisses!
- Oh. speak to me in your monotone voice.

248
00:13:21.968 --> 00:13:23.302
[both moaning]

249
00:13:23.303 --> 00:13:25.305
[moaning continues. muffled]

250
00:13:27.307 --> 00:13:30.434
[Homer. muffled] <i>Oh. yes. Seymour.
Oh. I love you. Seymour.</i>

251
00:13:30.435 --> 00:13:32.478
- [Marge] <i>Yes. Seymour! Yes. yes. yes!</i>
- [Homer moaning]

252
00:13:33.479 --> 00:13:35.356
[both] <i>Oh. Seymour!</i>

253
00:13:37.400 --> 00:13:40.027
[sighs] I love these little coffees.

254
00:13:40.028 --> 00:13:42.321
Each one tinier than the last.

255
00:13:44.657 --> 00:13:49.494
[spits loudly]

256
00:13:49.495 --> 00:13:50.496
Look.

257
00:13:52.874 --> 00:13:58.837
"Locals speculate that due to the corpse's
bloated state. bald head and awful smell.

258
00:13:58.838 --> 00:14:04.342
it is likely to be the body of
sexually ambiguous mooch Homer Simpsley."

259
00:14:04.343 --> 00:14:06.387
What? I don't look like a corpse.

260
00:14:09.182 --> 00:14:10.807
I guess I kinda see it.

261
00:14:10.808 --> 00:14:15.979
If they think you're dead. that means
they also think Skinner's still alive.

262
00:14:15.980 --> 00:14:18.524
We totally got away with it.

263
00:14:20.735 --> 00:14:22.612
[in Italian] That's him. officer.

264
00:14:23.404 --> 00:14:27.282
So. this Homer Simpsley lived
with you for a time.

265
00:14:27.283 --> 00:14:29.993
Is that correct. Mr. Skinner?

266
00:14:29.994 --> 00:14:32.621
Uh. you talking to me? 'Cause my name is--

267
00:14:32.622 --> 00:14:36.583
Yes. yes! Homer lived with us.
Lived off of us. I should say.

268
00:14:36.584 --> 00:14:39.336
He was a real... What's the Italian word?

269
00:14:39.337 --> 00:14:41.088
Uh. "moocharello."

270
00:14:41.089 --> 00:14:42.422
Exactly.

271
00:14:42.423 --> 00:14:47.969
This Simpsley character was nothing but
a leech. a sponge. a shiftless freeloader.

272
00:14:47.970 --> 00:14:50.430
Too stupid to make it in this world.

273
00:14:50.431 --> 00:14:54.851
{\an8}If you ask me. Homer was so torn up
about Seymour cutting him off

274
00:14:54.852 --> 00:14:58.438
that he likely jumped off a cliff
into the ocean.

275
00:14:58.439 --> 00:15:02.526
Well. it sounds like an
open-and-a-shut case of fatso "suicidio."

276
00:15:02.527 --> 00:15:05.112
And good riddance. right. Mr. Skinner?

277
00:15:05.113 --> 00:15:06.906
May Homer Simpsley rot in hell.

278
00:15:08.866 --> 00:15:10.742
"Dumb. ugly. lazy."

279
00:15:10.743 --> 00:15:13.662
How would you like it
if someone described you so accurately?

280
00:15:13.663 --> 00:15:16.998
I got that goombah gumshoe off our case.
didn't I?

281
00:15:16.999 --> 00:15:20.877
It'll be smooth sailing from here on out.
No more surprises.

282
00:15:20.878 --> 00:15:23.296
- [knock on door]
- [person] Surprise. Seymour.

283
00:15:23.297 --> 00:15:27.134
It's your best buddy Gary Chalmers.
I heard you were in Rome.

284
00:15:27.135 --> 00:15:30.887
Come on. Let's go to the Sistine Chapel
and pick up some broads.

285
00:15:30.888 --> 00:15:32.889
Look. no one's heard from you in weeks.

286
00:15:32.890 --> 00:15:36.226
I'm not leaving until
I see that you are... Oh.

287
00:15:36.227 --> 00:15:37.519
Simpsley?

288
00:15:37.520 --> 00:15:39.354
You meaty "moocharello."

289
00:15:39.355 --> 00:15:41.815
What are you doing in Skinner's apartment?

290
00:15:41.816 --> 00:15:43.150
Where's Seymour?

291
00:15:43.151 --> 00:15:45.443
Uh. he went to the Colosseum.

292
00:15:45.444 --> 00:15:47.070
I think the lions are playing.

293
00:15:47.071 --> 00:15:48.364
[grunts] Shut up.

294
00:15:49.240 --> 00:15:52.325
[Marge] You must be Gary. Seymour's out.

295
00:15:52.326 --> 00:15:56.581
But if you're dead set on seeing him.
join us for a drink.

296
00:15:57.415 --> 00:15:58.583
[Chalmers] Hmm.

297
00:15:59.750 --> 00:16:01.127
[Marge] Uh-huh?

298
00:16:02.879 --> 00:16:04.921
[Chalmers] So. who the devil are you?

299
00:16:04.922 --> 00:16:08.383
- I'm Marge. Seymour's new wife.
- [Chalmers grunts]

300
00:16:08.384 --> 00:16:09.467
<i>Cin cin.</i>

301
00:16:09.468 --> 00:16:11.178
New wife? [scoffs]

302
00:16:11.179 --> 00:16:14.347
Seymour would never marry
some tenement Tina like yourself.

303
00:16:14.348 --> 00:16:17.893
Look at those dishpan
eyes and thick Polish wrists.

304
00:16:17.894 --> 00:16:19.561
[laughs] It's true.

305
00:16:19.562 --> 00:16:21.771
And those cankles could hold up a wharf.

306
00:16:21.772 --> 00:16:25.651
[chuckles] I'm disliking you
less and less. Cheers.

307
00:16:27.862 --> 00:16:30.155
So. what's going on here. Simpsley?

308
00:16:30.156 --> 00:16:33.325
When did you go from
primate to fashion plate?

309
00:16:33.326 --> 00:16:35.952
Why. you almost look like Seymour.

310
00:16:35.953 --> 00:16:38.246
[chuckles] Uh. no. he doesn't.

311
00:16:38.247 --> 00:16:40.707
It's like you're almost trying to be him.

312
00:16:40.708 --> 00:16:45.337
Uh. I like to think that
Seymour's been rubbing off on me.

313
00:16:45.338 --> 00:16:46.796
Mmm.

314
00:16:46.797 --> 00:16:50.008
A toast to friends
rubbing off on each other.

315
00:16:50.009 --> 00:16:51.719
Hear. hear.

316
00:16:52.303 --> 00:16:54.054
[gasps] Skinner's ring.

317
00:16:54.055 --> 00:16:58.266
He'd die before taking that off.
I'm calling the police.

318
00:16:58.267 --> 00:17:00.144
But first. to finish my drink.

319
00:17:03.231 --> 00:17:06.566
Geez Louise. Is killing rich guys
your solution to everything?

320
00:17:06.567 --> 00:17:08.235
We're gonna get caught for sure.

321
00:17:08.236 --> 00:17:10.321
Shut up. I need to think.

322
00:17:14.909 --> 00:17:16.494
We can fix this.

323
00:17:21.249 --> 00:17:22.833
Meow.

324
00:17:29.173 --> 00:17:31.217
[Bart gasps] Mamma mia.

325
00:17:34.011 --> 00:17:36.430
{\an8}[in Italian] Too much wine for papa. eh?

326
00:17:37.265 --> 00:17:39.183
- [laughs]
- [chuckling] <i>Sì. sì.</i>

327
00:17:40.601 --> 00:17:42.186
[in English] Ay. Columbus.

328
00:17:45.898 --> 00:17:49.277
[choking] Son of a... [groaning]

329
00:17:51.862 --> 00:17:54.948
[in Italian] This one was bludgeoned.

330
00:17:54.949 --> 00:17:57.534
This one strangled to death.

331
00:17:57.535 --> 00:18:03.290
Whoever choked him really enjoyed it.

332
00:18:03.291 --> 00:18:06.460
Hey. Chief. I found something.

333
00:18:08.212 --> 00:18:11.756
[in English] Oh. my.
When Mr. Chalmers left last night.

334
00:18:11.757 --> 00:18:15.885
he said he was going to find some
Sicilians and insult their mothers.

335
00:18:15.886 --> 00:18:18.431
[gasps] Could that be a clue?

336
00:18:19.140 --> 00:18:20.390
Mmm.

337
00:18:20.391 --> 00:18:23.810
You're a very smart lady. signora Skinner.

338
00:18:23.811 --> 00:18:26.187
Very clever.

339
00:18:26.188 --> 00:18:31.026
But. unfortunately.
you are married to a stupid. stupid man.

340
00:18:31.027 --> 00:18:34.070
He's gonna confess and take you both down.

341
00:18:34.071 --> 00:18:36.907
It's just a matter of time.

342
00:18:40.036 --> 00:18:41.329
[shouting in Italian]

343
00:18:43.247 --> 00:18:45.541
[Homer shrieks]

344
00:18:47.376 --> 00:18:49.711
[Chief] It's the end of the road for you.

345
00:18:49.712 --> 00:18:54.799
Mrs. Skinner. because you
and your husband are free to go.

346
00:18:54.800 --> 00:18:56.468
Huh? Why?

347
00:18:56.469 --> 00:18:59.846
We arrested this <i>bastardo animalé</i>
trying to sell

348
00:18:59.847 --> 00:19:03.141
Mr. Chalmers's jewelry at a pawn shop.

349
00:19:03.142 --> 00:19:06.603
[in Italian] But I found it in the trash!

350
00:19:06.604 --> 00:19:10.149
Likely story. scumbag!

351
00:19:11.567 --> 00:19:14.986
[in English] What luck.
I almost confessed to everything.

352
00:19:14.987 --> 00:19:20.283
The murders. the fraud. trying all those
gelato flavors without ever buying any.

353
00:19:20.284 --> 00:19:23.703
Mmm. You certainly looked like
you were going to give us up.

354
00:19:23.704 --> 00:19:25.163
Oh. I was.

355
00:19:25.164 --> 00:19:27.332
But any time I was about to.
I remembered that

356
00:19:27.333 --> 00:19:29.876
you did whatever it took to protect us.

357
00:19:29.877 --> 00:19:33.505
To protect me. I've never had that before.

358
00:19:33.506 --> 00:19:35.966
I think... I think I love you.

359
00:19:37.218 --> 00:19:40.345
No one's ever said that to me before.

360
00:19:40.346 --> 00:19:44.683
My whole life. I've been on my own.
and now I realize having

361
00:19:44.684 --> 00:19:49.062
someone to scheme and scam
with has been all I ever wanted.

362
00:19:49.063 --> 00:19:51.065
I... I love you too.

363
00:19:52.525 --> 00:19:54.985
Let's celebrate. What do you wanna do?

364
00:19:55.778 --> 00:19:59.864
Why don't we rent a little boat
and go out in the middle of the ocean?

365
00:19:59.865 --> 00:20:01.158
[Homer] Mmm.

366
00:20:04.662 --> 00:20:05.745
[motor stops]

367
00:20:05.746 --> 00:20:09.624
Here's to a long.
loving and luxurious life together.

368
00:20:09.625 --> 00:20:10.626
[glasses clink]

369
00:20:11.836 --> 00:20:15.089
Hey. I forgot to ask. What's in that
really heavy bag you made me carry?

370
00:20:16.257 --> 00:20:19.092
Is it a surprise for me?

371
00:20:19.093 --> 00:20:21.052
[grunts. groans]

372
00:20:21.053 --> 00:20:24.931
- [gasping] Marge. why?
- I'm sorry. Homer.

373
00:20:24.932 --> 00:20:28.935
I do love you. but you are
bound to mess our good thing up.

374
00:20:28.936 --> 00:20:31.271
- [grunts]
- 'Cause you're a terrible liar.

375
00:20:31.272 --> 00:20:35.817
- and you're dumb. dumb. dumb. dumb.
- [grunting]

376
00:20:35.818 --> 00:20:38.195
[cries]

377
00:20:40.823 --> 00:20:41.824
Hmm.

378
00:20:42.616 --> 00:20:44.702
[grunts] Huh?

379
00:20:48.164 --> 00:20:51.791
Oh. honey. You were smart after all.

380
00:20:51.792 --> 00:20:54.503
[retches. straining]

381
00:20:59.842 --> 00:21:02.802
Dear Mr. Skinner.
I'm writing with sad news.

382
00:21:02.803 --> 00:21:04.721
Your mother has died.

383
00:21:04.722 --> 00:21:08.016
<i>She read your letter about your
hasty marriage and was so incensed</i>

384
00:21:08.017 --> 00:21:11.561
<i>that you found true love that
she choked on her broth and drowned.</i>

385
00:21:11.562 --> 00:21:14.355
She leaves the entirety
of her fortune to you.

386
00:21:14.356 --> 00:21:16.983
The board of directors
will run the family business.

387
00:21:16.984 --> 00:21:21.279
Leaving you and your new spouse free
to continue your life of spoiled excess.

388
00:21:21.280 --> 00:21:26.201
<i>On behalf of the firm.
we wish you both a long and happy union.</i>

389
00:21:26.202 --> 00:21:28.871
[♪ Italian music playing]

389
00:21:29.305 --> 00:22:29.469
